A healthcare worker prepares to conduct a PCR Covid-19 test. AFP/Emmanuel Croset JOHANNESBURG - South Africa has recorded 1,692 new COVID-19 cases in the past 24 hours. COVID-19 | WATCH | Mask rules to be re-examined 727 of those were identified in Gauteng with 361 in KwaZulu Natal and 330 in the Western Cape. All other provinces recorded less than 100 new cases. 10 deaths were reported by the Department of Health with one occurring in the past 24-48 hours. In the past two years, the country has seen more than three million positive cases and over 100,000 people have died. #COVID19 UPDATE: 27,832 tests were conducted in the last 24hrs, with 1,692 new cases, representing a 6.1% positivity rate. Today @HealthZA reports 10 deaths; of these, 1 occurred in the past 24–48 hours. Total fatalities are 100,042 to date. See more here: https://t.co/tbtP8K09Q0 pic.twitter.com/ri7gJ9hKNV